%[text] ## **Pump Sizing**
%[text] #### **Additional Piping, Fittings and Radiatior**
%[text] In the previous sections [ColdPlate](file:.\ColdPlate.mlx) we have already determined expected pressure losses at nominal conditions for the cold plate. Adding to that, there will be additional pressure losses from pipings, fittings and radiator. We will determine length of piping and the aggregated equivalent length of additional fittings. We are assuming an overall piping length of 3 m and we will roughly account for the equivalent length of 4 90° elbow bends. 
%[text] Only a small pressure drop is expected for the radiator, we will add a margin to the overall pressure drop to account for this. 
%[text] 
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Piping length (m) | 3 |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | Piping diameter (mm) | 8 |
%[text] | Ratio of aggregate equivalent length of local resistances to hydraulic diameter  | 4\*60 |
%[text] | Piping roughness ($\\mu${"editStyle":"visual"}m) | 15 |
%[text:table]
%%
%[text] #### Determine Pressure Drop for Additional Piping
pipingD         = simscape.Value(8, "mm");    % Additional diameter
pipingDh        = pipingD;                    % Hydraulic diameter
pipingLength    = simscape.Value(3, "m");     % Additional piping length
equivalentLengthRatio = 4*60;
equivalength    = equivalentLengthRatio*pipingDh;
pipingAddLength = simscape.Value(1, "m");     % Aggregate length of additional components
pipingArea      = pi*(pipingD/2)^2;           % Additional elements cross-sectional area
pipingRoughness = simscape.Value(15e-6, "m"); % Piping roughness
%[text] Determine pressure loss in Simscape model
open_system("example_Piping")
%[text] ![](text:image:1e09)
%[text] Again, we are using a Pipe (TL) block to represent the additional piping and fitting elements. The pipe geometry is parameterized the above values. As in previous models we set the cross-sectional areas of connected ports to similar values. Here, this is chosen to be the piping cross-sectional area. 
simInp = Simulink.SimulationInput("example_Piping");
simInp = simInp.setModelParameter("StopTime","250");

simOut = sim(simInp);

pPipingIn       = simOut.simlog.Pipe_TL.A.p.series.values("bar");
pPipingOut      = simOut.simlog.Pipe_TL.B.p.series.values("bar");

dpPiping        = simscape.Value(pPipingIn-pPipingOut, "bar");

figure %[output:343aa367]
plot(simOut.tout,[pPipingIn,pPipingOut]) %[output:343aa367]
ylabel("p [Pa]") %[output:343aa367]
xlabel("Time [s]") %[output:343aa367]
legend("p_{Coolant,In}","p_{Coolant,Out}") %[output:343aa367]
hold off %[output:343aa367]

disp(dpPiping(end)) %[output:563069d2]

%%
%[text] #### Pump Parameterization
%[text] The overall pressure drop determined for the cold plate (in [ColdPlate](file:.\ColdPlate.mlx)) and the additional piping is roughly 0.35 bars. Adding a margin to account for uncertainties as well as the pressure losses caused by the radiator, we will work with a overall pressure loss value of 0.4 bars. The system will be modeled using a [Centrifugal Pump (TL)](https://www.mathworks.com/help/hydro/ref/centrifugalpumptl.html) which offers several different parameterization options. 
%[text] We will work with a representative vendor data sheet and extract the pump curves for use in the Simscape block. In the parameterization option 1D tabulated data - head and break power vs. capacity at reference speed, the pump head and break power and respective capacity will be provided as a lookup table. The data sheet used is:
%[text] ![](text:image:1efe)
%[text] 
%[text] We can use the [Graph Data Extractor](https://www.mathworks.com/help/simscape/ref/graphdataextractor.html) to extract the points for the relevant pump model:
%[text] ![](text:image:1898)
%[text] Load values from the previously created Graph Data Extractor session. See the script [createPumpData](file:..\Docs\createPumpData.m) how the data from the Graph Data Extractor is processed. 
load("Data\pumpData.mat")
%[text] We will use a  pump inertia value of 1e-5 kg\*m^2. 
pumpInertia     = simscape.Value(1e-5, "kg*m^2"); 
pumpRefSpeed    = simscape.Value(2850, "rpm");
%%
%[text] Next, we will test the pump in a Simscape model:
open_system("example_Pump")
%[text] ![](text:image:2371)
%[text] The test model uses a Pressure Source (TL) block to mimic a load, we use an Inport block connected to that to load a test vector into the model. To test the pump range, we ramp up the load beyond the expected maximum pressure drop. You can also validate the pump curve with the current parameterization by right-clicking the pump component and selecting *Fluids-\>Plot Pump Characteristics:*
%[text] ![](text:image:9b1e)
%[text] Note that there is also an Inertia component connected to the mechanical R port of the pump. It is good practice to add an inertia (or compliance) to avoid instabilities with instantaneous changes.  Additionally, the Simulink-PS conversion block attached to the pump velocity input is configured to filter the input signal (indicated by the black dot on the block icon), for this specific model this is required to solve this model. This stems from how Simscape is solved and when converting a Simulink signal to a PS signal, the relevant state is reduced and missing information, to resolve this, the *Input Handling* setting in the block is activated, and set to filter (alternatively, signal derivatives could be provided as additional information). Here, first-order filtering is sufficient, it is good practice to set the time constant filter to a value larger than an expected time step, so larger than expected model dynamics. (Read more in the [Input Handling](https://www.mathworks.com/help/simscape/ref/simulinkpsconverter.html#mw_15965d02-3ff1-479a-84af-76f3d171f8ca) section in the documentation of the block). 
filterConst = simscape.Value(0.002, "s");
dpReq = simscape.Value(0.4, "bar");                                      % Pressure losses used for testing

tInPumpTest     = [0;60];  
loadInPumpTest  = [dpReq.value("bar");dpReq.value("bar")];               % Pressure load used for testing 
speedInPumpTest = [2600;3200];                                           % Pump speed used for testing 
speedInit       = simscape.Value(speedInPumpTest(1),"rpm");              %#ok<NASGU> used by Simulink model

simInp = Simulink.SimulationInput("example_Pump");
simInp = simInp.setModelParameter("StopTime",string(tInPumpTest(end)));
simInp = simInp.setExternalInput([tInPumpTest,loadInPumpTest,speedInPumpTest]);
simOut = sim(simInp);

pLoad = simOut.simlog.Pressure_Source_TL.P.series.values("bar");
VDotPump  = simOut.simlog.Centrifugal_Pump_TL.q_A.series.values("lpm");
speedPump = simOut.simlog.Centrifugal_Pump_TL.omega.series.values("rpm");
effPump = simOut.simlog.Centrifugal_Pump_TL.efficiency.series.values("1");

figure %[output:3aa9bc2c]
yyaxis left %[output:3aa9bc2c]
plot(speedPump,pLoad); %[output:3aa9bc2c]
ylabel("\DeltaP [bar]") %[output:3aa9bc2c]
yyaxis right %[output:3aa9bc2c]
plot(speedPump,VDotPump); %[output:3aa9bc2c]
ylabel("Flow rate [lpm]") %[output:3aa9bc2c]
xlabel("Pump speed [rpm]") %[output:3aa9bc2c]
legend("Pump \DeltaP","Pump flow rate") %[output:3aa9bc2c]
grid on %[output:3aa9bc2c]
figure %[output:0bea302b]
plot(speedPump,effPump*100); %[output:0bea302b]
ylabel("Pump efficiency [%]") %[output:0bea302b]
xlabel("Pump speed [rpm]") %[output:0bea302b]

%[text] 
%[text] In the speed range tested for the given pressure load, pump created between roughly 4 and 8 lpm. We determined an operating point of 5.75 lpm, for the desired cooling capacity. 
%[text] From the plot we can see, that this relates to roughly 2950 rpm.
pumpSpeed   = simscape.Value(2950, "rpm");
%%
%[text] #### Heat Produced by Pump
%[text] To design the radiator in the next step, we will also have to account for the heat produced by the pump. We will run the pump at nominal operating conditions and extract the heat from the Simscape logging object as well: 
tInPumpTest     = [0;10];  
loadInPumpTest  = [dpReq.value("bar");dpReq.value("bar")]; 
speedInPumpTest = [pumpSpeed.value("rpm");pumpSpeed.value("rpm")]; 
speedInit       = simscape.Value(speedInPumpTest(1),"rpm"); 

simInp = Simulink.SimulationInput("example_Pump");
simInp = simInp.setModelParameter("StopTime",string(tInPumpTest(end)));
simInp = simInp.setExternalInput([tInPumpTest,loadInPumpTest,speedInPumpTest]);

simOut = sim(simInp);

efficiencyPump = simOut.simlog.Centrifugal_Pump_TL.efficiency.series.values("1");
mechanicalPwrPump = simOut.simlog.Centrifugal_Pump_TL.mechanical_power.series.values("W");
heatPump = (1-efficiencyPump).*mechanicalPwrPump;

figure %[output:0d5366b0]
plot(simOut.tout,heatPump); %[output:0d5366b0]
xlabel("Time [s]") %[output:0d5366b0]
ylabel("[W]") %[output:0d5366b0]
%%
%[text] #### Accumulator
%[text] We can use the current parameterization to determine the total fluid volume in all blocks that have an internal fluid volume, which are the Pipe blocks used to model the cold plate, the Heat Exchanger used to model the Radiator and the Pipe block used to account for additional piping. That adds up to roughly 1.93 kg. In a closed-loop cooling system an accumulator or a tank can act as a additional volume buffer to absorb temperature and pressure fluctuations. We will include an accumulator component to handle fluctuations, fluid expansion and act as a fluid reserve. 
%[text] Adding a volume of 5% is a reasonable margin. 
accumulatorFluidMass        = simscape.Value(1.93*0.05, "kg");
accumulatorFluidVolumeCalc  = accumulatorFluidMass/rhoCoolant;
%[text] Assuming that initially the accumulator is half filled at the beginning with the above calculated amount of fluid, the total accumulator volume will be twice that, rounded up, that will be roughly 0.2 l. We use the [Gas-Charged Accumulator (TL)](https://www.mathworks.com/help/hydro/ref/gaschargedaccumulatortl.html) component. It represents a pressurized thermal liquid container with a compressed gas charge. To model the component, this requires additionally a precharge pressure for the gas volume. It describes the gas pressure and volume from the precharge statesusing the polytropic equation (see also [Chamber Volumes](https://www.mathworks.com/help/hydro/ref/gaschargedaccumulatortl.html?searchPort=56514#mw_532003f7-6dcf-4391-b34f-4f34cbd0e089)). We will use this to derive the precharge pressure based on our assumptions for initial liquid volume. Note, that the precharge pressure is expressed as gauge pressure. The initial pressure are assumed to be at the initial loop pressure.  
accumulatorTotalVolume  = simscape.Value(1, "l");
accumulatorMinGasVolume = accumulatorTotalVolume*0.01;
accumulatorGasK         = simscape.Value(1.4, "1");

accumulatorInitVolumeL  = accumulatorTotalVolume/2;
accumulatorInitVolumeG  = accumulatorTotalVolume-accumulatorInitVolumeL;
accumulatorPreChargeP   = pLoop*accumulatorInitVolumeG^accumulatorGasK/(accumulatorTotalVolume^accumulatorGasK)-simscape.Value(1, "atm");
%[text] Additionally the component models hard-stops when reaching minimum or maximum capacity. Hard stop stiffness and damping parameters are used to model this effect. Depending on the values chosen, the volume can momentarily be above capacity or below zero. Along with the accumulator component, we will connect a [Flow Resistance (TL)](https://www.mathworks.com/help/simscape/ref/flowresistancetl.html) block to the circuit, thje accumulator itself models no flow resistance between, adding a small flow resistance allows to separate the accumulator's node state from the connected components. 
accumulatorStopK      = simscape.Value(1e4, "MPa/m^3");
accumulatorStopD      = simscape.Value(1e4, "MPa*s/m^6");

flowResistandDpNom    = simscape.Value(1e-4, "MPa");
flowResistandMdotNom  = simscape.Value(0.1, "kg/s");

%[text] We will test the parameterization with a model:
open_system("example_AccumulatorPressure")
%[text] ![](text:image:6315)
%[text] We will test the behaviour over a range of operating conditions. The first test will use use pressure pulses causing in and outflow of the accumulator.:
%% Parameters for square waveform
A      = 2;         % pulse amplitude (bar)
PRF    = 0.1;       % pulse repetition frequency (Hz)
PW     = 1/PRF/2;   % pulse width (seconds)
fs     = 10;        % sampling rate (Hz) -- choose fs >> 1/PW
Ttotal = 60;        % total duration (seconds)

% Derived
PRI = 1/PRF;                                % pulse repetition interval
t   = 0:1/fs:Ttotal-1/fs;                   % time vector

% Rectangular pulse (0 and 1) scaled by amplitude
pulseEnvelope = double(mod(t,PRI) < PW);  % logical envelope
tInAccumulatorTest         = t';
pressureInAccumulatorTest  = A * pulseEnvelope'-1;              % Pressure waveform used for testing 

figure %[output:11437d24]
plot(t,pressureInAccumulatorTest) %[output:11437d24]
xlabel("Time [s]") %[output:11437d24]
ylabel("[bar]") %[output:11437d24]
legend("Test input pressure") %[output:11437d24]
 
simInp = Simulink.SimulationInput("example_AccumulatorPressure");
simInp = simInp.setModelParameter("StopTime",string(tInAccumulatorTest(end)));
simInp = simInp.setExternalInput([tInAccumulatorTest,pressureInAccumulatorTest]);
simOut = sim(simInp);

pressureAccumulator = simOut.simlog.Accumulator.p_I.series.values("bar");
volumeAccumulator   = simOut.simlog.Accumulator.liquid_volume.series.values("l");
massFlow            = simOut.simlog.Accumulator.mdot_A.series.values("kg/s");
 
figure %[output:80746016]
yyaxis left %[output:80746016]
plot(simOut.tout,volumeAccumulator); %[output:80746016]
hold on %[output:80746016]
plot([simOut.tout(1),simOut.tout(end)],[accumulatorTotalVolume.value("l"),accumulatorTotalVolume.value("l")],Color = [ 0.7520, 0.3600, 0.9840], LineStyle = ":"); %[output:80746016]
xlabel("Time [s]") %[output:80746016]
ylabel("[l]") %[output:80746016]
yyaxis right %[output:80746016]
plot(simOut.tout,pressureAccumulator); %[output:80746016]
ylabel("[bar]") %[output:80746016]
legend("Volume_{Accumulator,Liquid}","Capacity", "Pressure_{Accumulator,Liquid}") %[output:80746016]
hold off %[output:80746016]
%[text] We can see, that the liquid volume stays well within the capacity for the given pressure input. 
%[text] Next, we will test how it behaves at thermal expansion by applying a heat source to the accumulator. 
open_system("example_AccumulatorHeatFlow")
%[text] ![](text:image:6dc8)
%[text] We will apply a cpnstant heat flow rate to cause thermal expansion in the accumulator:
tInAccumulatorTest         = [0;150];
heatFlowInAccumulatorTest  = [500;500];   % W 

simInp = Simulink.SimulationInput("example_AccumulatorHeatFlow");
simInp = simInp.setModelParameter("StopTime",string(tInAccumulatorTest(end)));
simInp = simInp.setExternalInput([tInAccumulatorTest,heatFlowInAccumulatorTest]);
simOut = sim(simInp);

pressureAccumulator     = simOut.simlog.Accumulator.p_I.series.values("bar");
volumeAccumulator       = simOut.simlog.Accumulator.liquid_volume.series.values("l");
temperatureAccumulator  = simOut.simlog.Accumulator.T_I.series.values("degC");


figure %[output:2bf5fecd]
yyaxis left %[output:2bf5fecd]
plot(simOut.tout,pressureAccumulator); %[output:2bf5fecd]
hold on %[output:2bf5fecd]
xlabel("Time [s]") %[output:2bf5fecd]
ylabel("[bar]") %[output:2bf5fecd]
yyaxis right %[output:2bf5fecd]
plot(simOut.tout,temperatureAccumulator); %[output:2bf5fecd]
ylabel("[°C]") %[output:2bf5fecd]
legend("Pressure_{Accumulator,Liquid}","Temperature_{Accumulator,Liquid}") %[output:2bf5fecd]
hold off %[output:2bf5fecd]

figure %[output:9e215b21]
plot(simOut.tout,volumeAccumulator); %[output:9e215b21]
xlabel("Time [s]") %[output:9e215b21]
ylabel("[l]") %[output:9e215b21]
legend("Volume_{Accumulator,Liquid}") %[output:9e215b21]
%[text] For the given scenario the fluid heats up to well over 60 °C pressure and volume stay well within given ranges. 

